               <note xml:id="d2e1026" n="10"> On this form see vol. 3, Aaron (2) B/M, p.
                        75.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e1036" n="11"> The
                            inscription comes from the antiquities market. The man who produced this
                            inscription claimed that it comes from a place associated with Abraham.
                            Mordtmann understood this to refer to Hebron.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e1050" n="12"> This inscription was
                            presumably found in Hebron. It mentions the biblical Abraham, Isaac and
                            Aaron. It could be Jewish but is could of course just as likely be
                            Christian, see vol. 3, Introduction 6.6.7, p. 52. </note>
               <note xml:id="d2e1057" n="13"> The inscription is not dated. Late antique date
                            presumed, see vol. 3, Introduction 8.3, p. 60.</note>
            </person>
